narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: solving cooperative games and understanding some of the theory.
Matching algorithms, Shapley value, Nash bargaining, how to find Nash Equilibria, and a number of other smaller topics

This class is so interesting and covers a really interesting side of game theory that is not touched upon in other game theory classes at Yale. In just one semester of lectures, it covered 6 groundbreaking, Nobel Prize winning topics in game theory at a level where every student truly understood the content.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: I think this course is awesome! It teaches so effectively and is very engaging along the way. The assignments are well-related to the topics taught in class and only serve to improve students' understanding.

Professor Dubey is extremely knowledgeable about game theory. He is clearly excited to teach the material. He is also extremely accommodating of his students with regards to assignment extensions, course pace, etc. 

One thing that made the course material more difficult for me to keep up with was the fact that the class met once a week for 2 hours, as opposed to twice a week. At times it was a lot of material at once, and also the weekly class set up made it such that it was easy to disengage from the class at times.

Overall a great course that I would highly recommend!

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Professor Dubey is a knowledgeable and engaging lecturer. If you would like to get a laid-back survey of topics in game theory (with a focus on cooperative scenarios) that does not assume and prior knowledge, this class would be a great fit.
Yes, for any student who likes game theory and wants to learn more, this class is excellent!

Yes I would. It is a well taught course run by a very smart, passionate, and engaged professor. In addition, the assignments are very reasonable, and feel like they are actually reinforcing class concepts rather than just serving as busy work.
Absolutely! Pradeep is great teacher and teaches in a fun way.
Yes, good seminar to take if you have proof experience.
